Algorithm: K-Means

Run in this order:
-pdftotxt (coverts all pdfs to txt files, delete the garbage text in the borders)
-Abstract_Concadenation (Reads all text files and writes them into a new text file)
-Abs_Extr (Gives the proper format. Extracts the titles and abstracts into 2 diferent files: scores and testt)
-FinalCode (Uses the scores and testt files to cluster them)

NOTES:

-Make sure to put all abstracts into the correct folder.

-Make sure to have "doc_cluster.pkl" file downloaded. It wont be able to cluster without this file

-There's some formating that need to be done before running "FinalCode".
Check that the number of titles("scores" file) are the same as the number of texts,as well as making sure that for
every title is written in a different line and only one("test" file) otherwise it will be an error.

-If you just want to see the final result, run the "FinalCode" with "scores" and "testt" files

To get the proper value of N (number of clusters), you should run the "ElbowMethod" file, which is located in "PERCDocClusters".
This escencially adds all the error distances (distance from each document to its respective cluster) and squares it. After that,
it plots a number of clusters vs average error distance graph. You should see an exponential decay. The proper value of N would be
at the point where the slope changes most drastically.

Final Result:
To get this, I used N=7, which is the number of clusters. On top of every cluster title,
There are the most tfidf-weighted words/terms. The Final result wont be in the same every time, this is due to the fact that
K-means selects random centroids each time the code is ran, therefore, different clusters are generated. This is the result I got,
you can get different clusters, but when plotting it using "testing" file many times, you should see some kind of consistent behavior :


